[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT]    extracted_file_text: 1. What specific key points from the Day 1, 2, and 3 conference talks were most striking to
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] you? Give one concrete learning for each conference talk.
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] - The first day's discussion on vocation led to the realization that studying is a sacred
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] obligation to find truth and develop holiness, not just to pass exams. Inspired by St.
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] Thomas Aquinas, I learned that seeking truth requires courage, even if it means
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] sacrificing comfort or opposing corruption. The second day broadened my
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] understanding of love, defining it as the purposeful pursuit of the other person's
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] unconditional well-being, persevering through changing emotions and trials. Finally,
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] the third day's mission reflection emphasized that hope is absorbed through
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] inspiration and companionship, caught by believing in a person's greatest qualities
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] through shared experiences.
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] 2. How did the university retreat help you personally? What aspects of your life you felt the
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] retreat became most helpful?
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] - The university retreat helped me confront the pessimism that had inadvertently
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] seeped into my heart regarding love and relationships. I realized my tendency to
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] anticipate failure or shield myself from disappointment was a form of despair,
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] impeding necessary personal development. The retreat also reframed my academic
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] life, helping me view my education as a vocation intertwined with spiritual
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] development, rather than a mere duty. This gave me clarity: my goal as a Thomasian
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] student is to seek truth with integrity and let knowledge guide me toward holiness.
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] 3. After attending the ALAB 2026 UST retreat, what concrete personal actions will you
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] undertake to respond to the call of the retreat of “missionary rekindling” as a Thomasian
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] student? How do you bear witness to the retreat’s theme, “ALAB 2026:
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] Pananampalataya, Pag-asa, Pag-ibig?
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] - I will integrate prayer into my studies, viewing my academic work as a holy pursuit
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] of truth and holiness, thereby answering the missionary call. I will practice the
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] pedagogy of hope by being truly present with classmates, believing in their potential
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] so that hope is caught, not just taught. I will intentionally choose to will the good of
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] others, even when feelings fade, allowing love to be refined and endure through
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] challenges, instead of retreating into cynicism. By trusting God's timing over my own
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] wishes, I will avoid arrogance and despair. I will embody the ALAB 2026 theme
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] letting the fires of truth, love, and hope transform my life by living faith through my
[2026-04-05 01:01:37.275] [PRINT] studies, hope through companionship, and love through thoughtful choices.
